definition.value: A leukotriene that is leukotriene E4 in which the non-conjugated double bond has been reduced to a single bond.
An icosanoid that is leukotriene E3 in which the terminal octyl group is replaced by a carboxymethyl group.
A spirostanyl glycoside that consists of the trisaccharide alpha-L-Rha-(1->4)-[alpha-L-Rha-(1->2)]-beta-D-Glc attached to position 3 of diosgenin via a glycosidic linkage.
A 16-carboxy-Delta(13)-17,18,19,20-tetranor-leukotriene E4 in which the double bond at position 13-14 has E-configuration.

An S-hydrocarbyl-L-cysteine that is L-cysteine in which the  hydrogen attached to the sulphur is replaced by a prop-2-enyl group. It commonly occurs in garlic and has been found to exhibit antineoplastic activity.
An S-substituted L-cysteine where the S-substituent is specified as (2-hydroxyethyl)sulfane.
An aldonolactone obtained by formal oxidation of the anomeric position of any aldopyranose.
A dipeptide formed from glycine and L-methionine residues.
A glutamic acid derivative with a methylsulfanyl group  at position 4.
A pyrimidine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is the mono-p-nitrophenyl ester of thymidine 5'-monophosphate.
A monohydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of 3-dimethylallyl-4-hydroxybenzoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A lactam in which the amide bond is contained within a five-membered ring, which includes the amide nitrogen and the carbonyl carbon.
A pyrrolidinone in which the oxo group is at position 2 of the pyrrolidine ring.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having (9Z,12Z)-octadeca-9,12-dienoyl as the 2-O-acyl group.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 17:0 in which the acyl group at position 1 is 1-heptadecanoyl and the hydroxy group at position 2 is unsubstituted.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 20:3 in which the acyl group at position 1 is (5Z,8Z,11Z)-icosatrienoyl (meadoyl) and the hydroxy group at position 2 is unsubstituted.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 20:4 in which the acyl group at position 1 is (5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z)-icosatetraenoyl (arachidonoyl) and the hydroxy group at position 2 is unsubstituted.
A L-threonine derivative that is L-threonine attached via its side-chain to FMN via a phosphate linkage.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 22:5 in which the acyl group at position 1 is (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z)-docosapentaenoyl and the hydroxy group at position 2 is unsubstituted.
A lysophosphatidylcholine in which the acyl group (position not specified) contains 22 carbons with 5 double bonds.
A lysophosphatidylcholine in which the remaining acyl group (position not specified) contains 24 carbons and 0 double bonds.
A lysophosphatidylcholine in which the remaining acyl group (position not specified) contains 24 carbons and 1 double bond.
A lysophosphatidylcholine in which the remaining acyl group (position not specified) contains 26 carbons and 0 double bonds.
A lysophosphatidylcholine in which the remaining acyl group (position not specified) contains 26 carbons and 1 double bond.
A phosphatidylcholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are (9Z)-hexadecenoyl and (13Z,16Z)-docosadienoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine O-38:0 in which the alkyl and acyl groups (located at positions 1 and 2 respectively) are octadecyl and icosanoyl.
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the N-acyl group is specified as docosanoyl
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the N-acyl group is specified as (13Z)-docosenoyl.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and glycine residues.
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the N-acyl group is specified as (15Z)-tetracosenoyl.
A thiol that is glycerol in which one of the primary hydroxy groups is replaced by a thiol group.
A phosphorus oxoanion obtained by selective deprotonation of the SH goup and one of the OH groups of dithiophosphoric acid.
A methyl lactate that has R configuration.
A chlorophyllide obtained by hydrolysis of the terpenoid ester moiety of 3-vinylbacteriochlorophyll a.
A sulfur-containing amino acid that is L-aspartic acid substituted at position 3 by a thio (sulfanyl) group.
A phosphatidylcholine 34:1 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and palmitoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 36:2 in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both oleoyl.
A  phosphatidylcholine 36:3 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and linoleoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 38:5 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and arachidonoyl respectively.
A uridine 5'-phosphate that is the 5,6-dihydro derivative of uridine 5'-monophosphate.
A phosphorus oxoanion obtained by selective deprotonation of two of the three phosphate OH groups of thiophosphoric acid.
Any sulfate salt resulting from the formal condensation of aluminium hydroxide with 1.5 mol eq. of sulfuric acid.

A hydrate resulting from the the formal combination of anhydrous aluminium sulfate with approximately 18 mol eq. of water. The commercial product usually contains 5-10% less water than theory. It is one of the commonest hydrates of aluminium sulfate.
A hydrate resulting from the the formal combination of anhydrous aluminium sulfate with approximately 16 mol eq. of water. It is one of the commonest hydrates of aluminium sulfate.
Any organic aromatic compound having one or more hydroxy groups attached to a heteroarene ring.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as linoleoyl and oleoyl respectively.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl substituent is specified as linolenoyl (9Z,12Z,15Z-octadecatrienoyl).
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as linolenoyl and oleoyl respectively.
The ammonium salt formed from association of two ammonium cations with the dianion of 12-aminolauroyl tripalmitoyl cardiolipin.
